To everyone who has ever downloaded Bumble, loved Bumble, left Bumble, chosen not to use Bumble, or wished it could be better—this is for you. You deserve better. Over the years, finding love online has lost its way and it’s our commitment to you to change that. Every decision we’re making will be driven by one goal—bringing love back to the center of it all.

Have suggestions on how we can better your Bumble experience? Click the link in our bio to hear more from our Founder & CEO Whitney Wolfe Herd and to share your feedback.

To our members 

You came to us with a clear message—you want real people, real profiles, and a safer space to date. 

So, we’re rolling out government ID verification. Because you deserve to know that the people you're connecting with have confirmed their identity.

Thanks for helping us build the community you deserve.

Love, all of us at Bumble

Para todas las personas que alguna vez se descargaron Bumble, amaron Bumble, dejaron Bumble, decidieron no usar Bumble o simplemente desearon que fuera mejor, esto es para vosotras. Me preguntáis muchas veces qué me gusta de España, por qué Madrid es mi ciudad.
Veniros a experimentar el Orgullo y lo entenderéis, entre otras cosas. Si pudiera, habría inmortalizado este día en un gran fresco con pintura saturada que habría titulado: “la vida, la de verdad ”. Sigo viendo a esas abuelas en los balcones bailando reguetón. Pienso en esta mujer que daba el pecho a su hij@ con un brazo y nos saludó con el otro. Y no puedo dejar de repetirme el lema de esta madre acompañada de sus dos hijos: “¡Viva los gays porque salieron de mi vagina! » 
Es una ciudad donde primero reivindicamos y luchamos y luego celebramos y perreamos, siempre. El Día Internacional del Orgullo LGBT va más allá de los derechos LGBT. Celebramos la diversidad sexual, racial y corporal. Celebramos las expresiones e identidades de género, las orientaciones sexuales y románticas, los cuerpos gordos y flacos, los colores de piel: al ritmo de la sal del sudor y las lágrimas.

A tí Madrid, y a vosotr@s por ser tan maravillos@s 

Mensaje traducido : 

Camilleeeee te vi bailando como nunca en la carroza de Bumble ayer en el desfile de Madrid. Creo que eras tú, solo podías ser tú con tus grandes gafas y tu abanico. Le estabas enviando corazones a todas las personas con las que te encontrabas. Era increíble la energía que te rodeaba. Estoy con mi chico aquí en Madrid para el orgullo, no estoy out y él tampoco, y no puedo ni describir lo que sentí al verte aquí, es como si estuviera haciendo mi coming out a una parte de Francia. Me consoló, rompí a llorar justo después. Ver un rostro que conozco entre millones de personas. No nos viste pero nos sentimos vistos, aceptados, amados. Así que gracias por salir de París, gracias por estar allí. Jemenbatsleclito por siempre.

@grindr #grindr #grindrpartner #ad

keep it real with Taken On Grindr  now you can choose to add a “Taken On Grindr” badge and timestamp to photos taken using the in-app camera, visually confirming that both the image—and the user—are genuine, and that the photo was taken recently  developed as part of Grindr’s ongoing focus on Trust & Safety, “Taken On Grindr” gives your pixxx an xtra touch of authenticity

how it werks:
 an animated “Taken On Grindr” badge is applied to any photo taken through the in-app camera
 you can toggle the badge on or off during the photo-taking process
 the badge can be applied to any photo taken and sent through chat or uploaded as a profile photo

it’s #ZeroHIVStigmaDay ❤️ and Grindr is partnering with @preventionac to promote the de-stigmatizing U=U message to millions of global Grindr users.

U=U stands for Undetectable = Untransmittable, meaning that people living with HIV who have undetectable viral loads have zero risk of passing on HIV to sexual partners.

London Grindr users - order a @shldotuk test kit directly from the Grindr app.

SHL test kits are fast, discreet, and free. Delivered to your door.

Kits include STI and HIV tests. If you’re living with HIV you can still use the kits to test for STIs.

To order from the Grindr app - click on your photo image and look for the drop-down “Free STI kit” link in the side drawer menu. Click on the link to go straight to the SHL portal (see Image 2).

All data is held by SHL. No personal info is collected by or shared with Grindr.

Kits can also be ordered from - https://g4e.shl.uk (link in bio)

Photos @lucian.m.k 
Design @rkahwagi 

Image descriptions:

Image 1: A rotating carousel of five images shows a mock-up of a phone on a light pink background. The logos of The Love Tank, PrEPster and Grindr for Equality are at the top of the image. Large white block text reads: Free STI test kit. This is followed by smaller red text that says: Delivered to your door. Fast, discreet, and free. A yellow button has black text that says: Order my kit.

The above text is written in English for 3 of the 5 images, and in Portuguese and Spanish for 2 of the images.

Each image features two people in different levels of intimacy, including kissing. One of the images includes 2 people in pup masks.

Image 2: the images shows a mock-up of two phones screens, both against a light pink background. The image on the left shows the side drawer menu of a Grindr profile. It has a black background and the user’s photo at the top, with their username under. In white lettering beneath there are options that include: Free STI kit. 

The image to the right shows the web page of SHL, which is the page that links through when an individual clicks on the Free STI kit link on their Grindr side drawer menu. The SHL page has a white background, with detailed black lettering, and a larger blue button with white text that reads: Register to order. A white box below, with blue lettering reads: Login - I’m already registered.

“Two big things happened when I turned 18: I registered to vote, and I downloaded Tinder. I lived at home in a suburb of 8,000 people north of New York City. I was still in the closet. While my hometown is more liberal than most, I didn’t know many gay people in the area. Sure, I had heard about other gay men who were friends of friends, but given I had never actually met them, it wasn’t like I could hit them up and ask them to hang out. So, I took to Tinder to meet them and to try to discover what I was looking for — either in a romantic partner or new friends. Perhaps first and foremost, I did not want to go to college without ever having kissed a boy.” - Justin Crowe (@jus10crowe), 21

"When I was diagnosed in 1987, it was a death sentence, but not anymore.” In honor of #WorldAIDSDay, @theoldgays talk about HIV. 

Sponsored by @viivhealthcare: ‘HIV in View’, a first-of-its-kind photo gallery, is a collaboration between global specialist HIV company ViiV Healthcare and Shutterstock Studios to tackle the continued stigma, negative assumptions and fear surrounding HIV. By providing images of real people living with HIV today, ‘HIV in View’ aims to challenge outdated stereotypes and change the way the world views HIV. This World AIDS Day marks one year since the gallery’s launch, and the geographical reach of the collection now stretches across the world from Europe, to North and South America, Africa and East Asia.

Join @viivhealthcare in shifting the world’s perception of HIV at our link in bio

"40 years and we’re still working hard to find a cure for HIV/AIDS. I hope I get to see it in my lifetime, to celebrate a momentous achievement for so many people like me living with HIV.  

Today, with World Aids Day, I want to reflect on our fight, honor the ones who lost their battle to this virus, reflect on where we started to where we are now, and say thank you to those who continue to work so hard to end this epidemic.  

I want to celebrate the lives of those living with HIV today. Come together to help end the stigma and make it easier to talk about HIV, so people will look at us as simply human beings, because we are the same and shouldn't be treated as less than. That's why I have chosen to live my life openly, so everyone can see that I’m living my best life, beyond my status, because life truly is a celebration.”

“It was my freshman year of high school and the yearbooks had just came out. During gym class, my friends and I sat on the sidelines, flipping through all the senior photos. When we got to Jordan’s page, we stopped. The girls agreed he had the most handsome pic and I thought to myself: I’m going to be with that man someday.

The years came and went. In 2014, I broke off a long serious relationship and starting figuring myself out. In June, I graduated; in July, I came out as gay and turned 18; and by the time August rolled around, Jordan Maxwell had sent me a message on Grindr. Knowing who he was, remembering his yearbook photo from so many years ago, I did what anyone would do…I left him on read  I played hard to get for a month until we finally met up that October. We’ve been together ever since, and just got married last month.”

“I was traveling to Asia and the Pacific after I quit my job in Amsterdam. He was working in Singapore as an expat. Our story started with a tap on Grindr. We chatted for a few hours and the day after, he invited me over for lunch. That lunch ended up with us spending a few weeks together changing my travel plans altogether. But then Corona happened and I was forced to end my trip prematurely and return to Amsterdam. We were physically apart for almost six months. But our love figuratively moved mountains when we managed to be reunited last year despite the international borders shutting down. And in the next few months of living together, I proposed to him because I couldn’t bear a day without him in my life. And now we are happily spending our days as Mr. & Mr. Ooms-Valiente. Whoever said Grindr is not a way to find a husband is absolutely mistaken.”

We will not be silent. Black lives matter. ⁣
⁣
We were planning to announce our #PridePerseveres initiative today, but in light of the ongoing violence and injustices against our POC family, that no longer feels appropriate. How can we launch a month of celebration when so many of us are hurting? How can we celebrate Pride without acknowledging that we wouldn’t even HAVE a Pride month if it weren’t for the brave black, brown, trans, and queer folks whose uprising against the police at Stonewall gave birth to the modern LGBTQ+ rights movement? It is our responsibility to speak out against the hate and violence that such a vital part of our community continue to face.⁣
⁣
We stand in solidarity with the #BlackLivesMatter movement and the hundreds of thousands of queer people of color who log in to our app every day. We will not be silent, and we will not be inactive. Today we are making donations to the Marsha P. Johnson Institute @mpjinstitute and Black Lives Matter @blklivesmatter, and urge you to do the same if you can (links in bio). We will continue to fight racism on Grindr, both through dialogue with our community and a zero-tolerance policy for racism and hate speech on our platform. As part of this commitment, and based on your feedback, we have decided to remove the ethnicity filter from our next release.⁣
⁣
Tomorrow, we will announce our #PridePerseveres calendar, but in a different light. Yes, we can still come together in the spirit of Pride, but Pride this year has an added responsibility, a shifted tone, and a new priority that will be reflected in our programming—support and solidarity for queer people of color and the #BlackLivesMatter movement.

Hey Grindr! It is activist and writer @adameli taking over for part of the weekend to share a message in honor of #IntersexAwarenessDay and in response to America’s increasing transphobia. Many of us in the community, especially cis gay men, have certain privileges (such as visibility, safety, access to jobs +healthcare etc) that other members of the queer community do not. It is a waste of time to pretend like this privilege does not exist or to sit around feeling guilty about it. Instead we should leverage that privilege to create a more equal world by showing up for groups more marginalized than us.  Here are some ways to show up for the often disenfranchised and silenced intersex and trans community.

Showing up for the intersex community: Join the @voices4_ protest Saturday, repost the flyer to your story and head to the @intersexjusticeproject to learn about how we can help our intersex family.

Showing up for the trans community: Learn, talk and share about the #YesOn3 campaign! On Election Day, Massachusetts voters will face the first-ever statewide popular vote on protections for transgender people from discrimination. The referendum would repeal state law that protects transgender people from discrimination in public places, including restaurants, stores, doctor's’ offices and we can’t allow that to happen.

Today is #IntersexAwarenessDay!  Intersex refers to people who are born with any of a range of physical sex characteristics that don’t fit typical notions about male or female bodies. Variations may be in their chromosomes, genitals, or internal organs like testes or ovaries. Often intersex children are subjected to extensive, involuntary surgeries for no other reason than to make their bodies conform to traditional notions of what it means to be male or female. These surgeries often cause physical and psychological harm. Intersex surgeries are now considered human rights violations by groups like the United Nations, the World Health Organization, Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, and Physicians for Human Rights. However, such procedures are not directly prohibited in the United States, and they are still performed by a small group of specialists across the country. “Intersex people (who are born healthy) don’t need to be fixed, we need to fix the Binary. What’s not broken doesn’t need to be fixed” says Intersex Supermodel Hanne Gaby. 
### 
Follow @intersexjusticeproject @interact @voices4_ to learn more about supporting the intersex community!

#G4E (Grindr for Equality) launched something ⚡Over the past year we’ve been developing a database to help users in India locate #LGBTQ+ friendly sexual health, mental health and legal aid service providers.

The problem: Queer people in India still find it difficult to quickly locate HIV and other health and legal services. Even then, there are sensitivities around service providers being queer friendly.

The health service locator can help significantly reduce obstacles to finding LGBTQ+ friendly sexual health, mental health, and legal aid service providers in India.

This innovative database was created in partnership with Varta Trust and Solidarity and Action Against the HIV Infection in India (SAATHII). Varta Trust is an Indian gender and sexuality organization. SAATHII is a Chennai-based not-for-profit helping take action against HIV infection in India. Take a stand with us #G4E ✊

June 5, 1981 is a pivotal date in the history of the HIV/AIDS epidemic.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s the day the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) famously reported on the first cases of a “rare pneumonia” affecting young gay men living in New York and California. It would later be identified as #HIV/#AIDS.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Survivors are a valuable part of our communities. They are elders, leaders, and teachers. But often, they are isolated and rendered invisible. We must ensure that the voices and needs of long-term survivors are present as we continue to move forward.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Today, on HIV Long-term Survivor Awareness Day #HLTSAD2018, we honor the resilience and strength of #longtermsurvivors.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#ItIsStillNotOver

Matt & Michael #MetOnGrindr back in 2012 when they were both working in Downtown LA. Their Grindr chats developed into daily conversation. Matt moved back to Santa Barbara for school, but the magnetism between them turned into long distance texting, phone calls, and FaceTimes. After months of staying connected Michael went to visit Matt for a weekend where they had their first date. They’ve been dating ever since. The two now live together in Echo Park and are literal #relationshipgoals. 
⠀
“My understanding of love and companionship is very different from what it was before I met Michael. He’s the person who makes me laugh everyday, the person I share a secret language with, the person I turn to when life has me in a corner, the person I think about with every decision I make, the person I couldn’t imagine spending my life without.” - @in.this.dancery / @sassysissyboi

We’re celebrating #TransAwarenessMonth with new, more inclusive features to help trans and non gender conforming connect better.
⠀
Grindr users now have the option to customize gender identity and preferred pronouns. We’re also introducing a new Gender Identity Help Center so everyone can get up to speed on everything from gender definitions to how to respectfully message a trans person.
⠀
To get the message out, Grindr partnered with Emmy-nominated actress/writer and trans activist Jen Richards (@smartassjen) for “Hi! Bye!” In the video, Jen and friends have a funny but frank discussion about what to say (and what not to say) to a trans person with some help from a few Gaymoji-themed signs.

Iris Dating Tip #5: Think Before You Share Private Photos! 

 Never send private or intimate photos to someone you just met online. Scammers and bad actors can use them for blackmail, threats, or scams. 
 Stay safe by keeping personal images private. A real connection is built on trust, not pressure. If someone insists on getting private photos, it’s a red flag! 
#IrisDating #DatingTips #StaySafe #OnlineDating #PrivacyMatters #SmartDating #RedFlagAlert #ProtectYourself

Iris Dating Tip #4: Keep Your Private Info Private! 

Your personal details—phone number, address, workplace, and even last name—should stay private while chatting online. ️ 
Scammers and bad actors often use this info for fraud, scams, or even identity theft.
 Get to know someone first, build trust, and always prioritize your safety. 
If someone is pushing for your personal details too soon, it’s a red flag! 

#IrisDating #DatingTips #StaySafe #OnlineDating #PrivacyMatters #SmartDating #TrustButVerify #ProtectYourself

Iris Dating Tip #3: Never Send Money to Anyone! 

No matter the excuse—don’t send money to anyone you meet online!  
Scammers will use emotional stories, fake emergencies, or urgent requests to manipulate you.
 Real connections don’t come with a price tag. If someone asks for money, it’s a red flag. 
Stay safe, trust your instincts, and report any suspicious behavior.

#IrisDating #DatingTips #StaySafe #ScamAlert #RedFlag #OnlineDatingTips #SmartDating #NoMoneyNoScam #ProtectYourself

Iris Dating Tip #2: Don’t Delete Your Account Too Soon! 

We get it — moving to another communication channel is exciting!  But before you hit delete, remember: keeping your Iris account active is your safety net. ️
If something feels off or goes wrong, you’ll still have the power to report and help us track down any bad actors. 

Stay smart. Stay safe. Stay connected. 

#IrisDating #DatingTips #StaySafe #OnlineDating #RedFlagAlert #SmartDating #LoveWithConfidence

Red Flag Alert! 
If someone’s rushing to move the conversation off the app — it’s a major warning sign. Scammers often try to take things private to avoid detection. 
Stay safe. Stay on the app. ✨ We’ve got your back.
